  "duration": 76.02212864,
  "text": " Systems have distinct behaviors that are determined by the structure. To put it simply, the characteristics of the system, or the structure, drives its behavior. Let's look at classroom setup as an example. If a teacher wants students to watch them lecture and maybe take some notes, they should arrange desks into rows so that all students are facing the front, with few distractions. But if a teacher wants students to collaborate and work together, They might group desks together to make a huddle or table-like structure that encourages discussion and sharing. How you structure the room and the desks will affect the student's actions. Unlike the rules of a game, which are typically included in a package or available online, most of the systems we work with don't come with clear and concise printed instructions. Structures can be present in written or unwritten policies and procedures, social or organizational norms, power structures and dynamics, or through distribution of resources and institutionalized ways of working. Looking at the structure helps us analyze and begin to understand the ways in which the structure drives behavior. Using systems thinking, we are able to see not just what is happening, but also why it's happening.",
